               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18770917-731-charge-3" targOrder="Y" targets="def3-731-18770917 t18770917-731-offence-1 t18770917-731-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>731. <persName id="def1-731-18770917" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-731-18770917" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-731-18770917" type="age" value="33"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-731-18770917" type="surname" value="CHARLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-731-18770917" type="given" value="EMILY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EMILY CHARLTON</hi> (33)</persName>, <persName id="def2-731-18770917" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-731-18770917" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-731-18770917" type="age" value="37"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-731-18770917" type="surname" value="CHARLTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-731-18770917" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">EDWARD CHARLTON</hi> (37)</persName>, <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <persName id="def3-731-18770917" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def3-731-18770917" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-731-18770917" type="age" value="40"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-731-18770917" type="surname" value="CLAYTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def3-731-18770917" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY CLAYTON</hi> (40)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18770917-731-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18770917-731-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18770917-731-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp>, Stealing a chest of drawers and other articles, the property of <persName id="t18770917-name-464" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-464" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-464" type="surname" value="SEELEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-464" type="given" value="ARTHUR LEONARD"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18770917-731-offence-1 t18770917-name-464"></join>Arthur Leonard Seeley</persName>, in his dwelling-house.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. C. MATHEWS</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution;</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WARNER SLEIGH</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">appeared for Emily and Edward Charlton, and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">for Clayton.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-465" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-465" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-465" type="surname" value="SEELEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-465" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MART SEELEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Arthur Leonard Seeley, and now live at 15, Morton Street, Clerkenwell—in June last, I had words with my husband and he went away in a bit of temper, I remained at 2, Hornsey Park Road, where we were then living—Mr. and Mrs. Charlton lived at No. 3—when my husband left me I became intimate with Mrs. Charlton, who encouraged me to drink, and that went on till 5th July, when I removed to 86, Euston Road, by Mrs. Charlton's advice to avoid my husband—Mrs. Charlton ordered the vans and told me to "shut up" as I had nothing to do with it, and she would not allow me to say anything—on 4th July, I was very intoxicated and went to bed all the afternoon, I awoke between 3 and 4 o'clock next morning—I had not then quite recovered—I heard something moving about at the back of the house—I went into the back-room, and saw Clayton with a chest of drawers on his back—he put them over the wall to Mr. Charlton, and Mr. Charlton senior—they had all been packed full of goods ready for removal, by myself and a servant—afterwards Mrs. Charlton came upstairs and said "Make haste, the van is come"—I went to look, and saw a van—I said "How did you get into the house?"—she said "By the window"—I said "I fastened the window"—she said "Oh, we managed it," and when I went downstairs the kitchen window was wide open—I had employed Clayton to remove the things—the removal then took place, Mrs. Charlton taking part; I was about the house till the vans were loaded, when I and Mrs. Charlton got on the top of one to go to Euston Road—we went in a roundabout away to avoid anyone seeing me who knew me—Mrs. Charlton directed everything—she got down before we got to the Euston Road, because a man was following the vans, and she said "I don't know you "—we got there about 7 o'clock; I did not look over the things till a day or two afterwards, when I missed the things mentioned in this list (<hi rend="italic">pro<lb></lb>duced</hi>); afterwards Mrs. Charlton visited me and I asked her if she had any of the things—she said "I have not"—my husband joined me at Euston Road, and on 10th July, Mrs. Charlton came again—my husband was at home then—I begged her to give up the things"—I said "I am sure you had the things"—she said "I had not—I said "My husband will prosecute you unless you bring them back"—she said she had nothing belonging to me at first, and then she said "Yes, I will give them up"—I gave her a dress, and paid her 30<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for her trouble in removing the goods—I did not pay Mr. Charlton anything—I did not engage him; I paid Clayton 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—at the time of the removal I was possessed of 10<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. W. SLEIGH</hi>. This is the first time my husband left me—I had lived at Hornsey Park Road six weeks—my husband is a reader to the press—he lived there three out of the six weeks—he did not say he would not live with me any more—I swear that I did not get intoxicated before I knew Mrs. Charlton; I did not drink, except a glass of ale at meals when 1 felt inclined; not wine or spirits—drinking had nothing to do with the quarrel with my husband—we were half-quarterly tenants in</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170207"></xptr>
               <p>the Hornsey Road; 4<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was owing for rent when, we moved—we moved early in the morning to avoid my husband and not to avoid the landlord—Mrs. Charlton did not say the landlord's man was following the van; she did not know who he was—I did not then know that it was the land<lb></lb>lord's man—we moved on the Thursday, and we arrived in the Euston Road a little after 6 o'clock; the last piece of furniture was put in, I dare say, about 10 o'clock—it was put into two large rooms and remained there; I looked it—I did not miss anything then—I went with the detective to Mrs. Charlton's house the same day; I saw two pictures on the wall—I said at the police-court "I went with the detective to Charlton's house and saw the goods that I bad missed in the house, the pictures displayed on the wall, and the drawers were broken open"—the drawers were unlocked; I had the keys in my pocket—my husband spoke to me about the furniture—I heard him give his evidence at the police-court—I only knew the things were at Mrs. Charlton's house by seeing the drawers there—I told my husband that Charlton's had got the things without my consent or knowledge—I may not have used the word "stolen," but I said "They have the things," and I did not lead him to believe that they were minding the things—he blamed me for leaving Hornsey Park Road—I did not say the things were mine and I had a right to do what I liked with them—I lived at Harringay Road, Hornsey, in May, 1876, going on for three years—there was a bill of sale on the furniture, but I cannot say what date it was or the sum—I value this furniture at 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I lived at 6, Edith Terrace, Fulham, in 1875—I only knew of one bill of sale—we moved and the bill of sale went with us—Sarah Goodship was in our employment and was in the house when the things were removed—she attended at the police-court every day during the hearing; she was called by my solicitor—she knew nothing about it; then she was brought up by other parties—she was not put in the box by my solicitor—I arranged with Mrs. Charlton to come and knock us up early—the servant let her in—I locked up over night and saw all safe—the prisoners got in at the back window; the bolt was not broken——Mrs. Charlton did not say she got in through the window which the servant had left unbolted—Mrs. Charlton came upstairs when I was leaving the back room when I had seen the chest of drawers going over the wall—I did not complain to her about it. (<hi rend="italic">James Lovegrove was fare called in.</hi>) I know that man and I know Mr. Ward—those two men were engaged in the removal—I, Mrs. Charlton, and Sarah Goodship were looking out for the vans when they drove up to the door—I had not quite recovered, I was not sober—I did not speak to the carmen more than necessary—I did not know who Clayton was—I did not tell Sarah Goodship that some of the things were to go to her mother—I was not in the room when some things were taken to Mrs. Charlton's—I did not go to Mr. Goodship's house; I know him, he lives in the country—Mrs. Charlton was not in our house at the Euston Road at 10 o'clock—I did not send out for brandy or spirits.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi>. I finally went to bed about 12 o'clock on the 4th—I still say 1 was drunk then, but I locked up the house safely—I was never drunk before—I drank two glasses of port wine and 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. Worth of brandy; several shillings worth were sent for; Mrs. Charlton sent some "out for her child, who ill—I also had a glass of ale at 11 o'clock; I am not sure how much I drunk altogether—I was intoxicated when Mrs. Charlton advised me to go to bed—I did not say anything to the man when he was moving the drawers—Mrs. Charlton came upstairs then—the looking-glasses</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170208"></xptr>
               <p>were taken out of their frames and put in these drawers with some pictures, curtains, and a waterproof cloak, and a lot of things—Clayton put the drawers on the wall, and Mrs. Charlton took them—J did not say anything about it, I was so busy; not even when we arried at the Euston Road, I thought the man was moving them to the vans, I could not understand what he was doing—I did not ask him, I was so confused; I missed the things, but not when they were moving them in—I did not tell Lovegrove or Ward that Clayton was my husband—I did not on the day before the removal put the drawers one by one on Mrs. Charlton's little boy's head to take into his mother's; nothing of the kind took place—Clayton lodges in the same house with the Charlton's—about twenty minutes elapsed between the removal of the drawers and the arrival of the vans—I have not said "I think it is very unkind of Mrs. Charlton not to come and put the things straight, as I have given her a bedstead, a paliasse, a chest of drawers, and a washstand"—I saw my husband the day after I got to the Euston Road—he asked me what had become of the things, and I said I had seen the drawers go over the wall—he said I had done wrong and left me in anger—information was given to the police and the prisoners were given in custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Many of things were taken downstairs on 4th July, by my servant and Mrs. Charlton—the drink was taken at my house between 2 and 3 p.m.—while I was lying down she took the things downstairs; I have got the frame of the looking glass, Mrs. Charlton had the glass.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-466" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-466" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-466" type="surname" value="SEELEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-466" type="given" value="ARTHUR LEONARD"></interp>ARTHUR LEONARD SEELEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am now living at 16, Wharton Street, Clerkenwell, with my wife—on 6th July, I went to my wife in the Euston Road—in consequence of a communication she made to me I went with a van to Charlton's house on 10th July, at 3, Hornsey Park Road—I saw Mr. and Mrs. Charlton; I said I had come for my things, and "I am not going to be robbed in this way, I shall take proceedings against you"—Mrs. Charlton said "If your wife had had a charwoman in she would have robbed her a good deal more than I have"—I replied that there was no necessity for my wife to have a charwoman, as she had a servant; I went away then—I went again with my wife and a detective, and charged Mrs. Charlton with stealing the things, and gave her in custody; I do not remember whether she replied or not—we then searched the house and found the articles mentioned in the list, including the chest of drawers—the goods were removed to the police-station—their value would be about 12<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. W. SLEIGH</hi>. My wife did not lead me to believe that the Charlton's were minding these things—I said at the police-court "My wife told me when I went to her where the goods were," and "she did not say either that she had given them, or that they were minding them"—I do not think I said "From what she said I inferred they were minding them"—I did not intend that; it was read over tome—I said "Some goods were taken over the wall without her consent"—I have been separated from my wife once before, about two months ago, she has always been a temperate woman, drink had nothing to do with our separation—she had a separate income of her own—I went to Wood Green about this case, and the In<lb></lb>spector sent a man with me—no one else was present when Mrs. Charlton made the remark about the charwoman—when I first went I said that I should prosecute them—I did not threaten to give them in custody, I ex<lb></lb>pected to be abused and insulted, and I was.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170209"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. FULTON</hi>. When I went to the house I did not see Clayton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> The separation was not because of business, but because I was of a hasty temper—there was a slight separation and I left home for a few days.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-467" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-467" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-467" type="surname" value="CLARKE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-467" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH CLARKE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Detective Officer Y</hi>). On 11th July, I went with Seeley to 3, Hornsey Road, and took Mrs. Charlton in custody, she said the things were given to her by Mrs. Seeley, and "I was upstairs with Mrs. Seeley when they moved the things, and Clayton put the things over the wall, and my husband received them"—later in the day I saw Mr. Charlton, and charged him with receiving the things, knowing them to be stolen—he said "The things were given to me."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-468" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-468" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-468" type="surname" value="SKEATES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-468" type="given" value="CALEB"></interp>CALEB SKEATES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Detective Officer Y</hi>). I went with Clark to 3, Hornsey Park Road—after Mrs. Charlton was given in custody I searched the house and found the articles in the list produced, which were identified by Seeley as his property—I went again at 9 o'clock in the evening and saw Mr. Clarke, and took him in custody for being concerned with others in stealing furniture—he said "Very well, I will go with you"—afterwards he said "I assisted moving the goods, the only thing I put over the wall was a few coals."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-469" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-469" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-469" type="surname" value="SHIP"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-469" type="given" value="SARAH GOOD"></interp>SARAH GOOD SHIP</persName>
                  </hi>. I lived at Stevenage, in Hertfordshire, but now live at Finsbury Park—on 5th July, I was in Mrs. Seeley's service—I remember the removal from Hornsey Park Road, to the Euston Road—when we got there Mrs. Seeley said "I think it is very unkind of Mrs. Charlton not coming to put the things straight, as I gave her a wash-stand, a chest of drawers, and a bedstead"—I had seen a paliasse, and bedstead taken into Mrs. Charlton's house in the Hornsey Park Road—I helped to move the palliasse; Mrs. Seeley saw Mrs. Charlton, and me move it out of the room the day before the removal—Mrs. Seeley said "Mrs. Charlton may have the palliasse into her house"—Mr. Seeley had been away three weeks before the removal, she had been drinking on the previous Tuesday and for about a week—she used to send me for the drink, and Mrs. Seeley and Mrs. Charlton became very friendly together—Mrs. Charlton only came in when Mrs. Seeley sent for her; Mrs. Charlton came about 3 o'clock on the Thursday morning—I did not hear any arrangement made as to her coming; I did not Bee the drawers go over the wall—the wall is not very high, I could look over it, if I was not close to it, into the street without getting on anything—before we got to Euston Road, Mrs. Charlton left the van and came back to the Hornsey Road—the goods were being put into the other van and Mrs. Seeley was up and downstairs seeing to the goods—she gave Clayton half a sovereign on the road to get changed—in the evening between 6 and 7 o'clock, she gave Clayton 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. or 7<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 6<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I never heard Mrs. Seeley ask Mrs. Charlton to drink with her,' but Mrs. Seeley sent me to knock at the scullery door for Mrs. Charlton to come in; I cannot say what for—they drank together; that occurred once or twice a day—I came as a willing witness—when I came up I was out of a situation—Mr. and Mrs. Charlton gave me accommodation for one night—Mrs. Seeley said she gave Mrs. Charlton the things for moving—that was in Euston Road on the day of the removal—I looked surprised but did not say anything.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. MATHEWS</hi>. I came up to be a witness for Mr. Seeley, and said I knew nothing about it, except about the bed and bed-stead</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170210"></xptr>
               <p>—Mr. Seeley asked me to see Mr. Fenton—Mrs. Charlton came down on the Monday, and I was examined on the Wednesday—Mrs. Charlton paid my expenses—Mrs. Seeley was not sober on 4th July—I think I said in the other Court that I was to help Mrs. Charlton move the palliasse into her house—what I said was "Mrs. Seeley told me to help Mrs. Charlton move the mattress downstairs," but Mrs. Charlton was in the room and told me to help Mr. Charlton down with it and over the wall and up Mrs. Charlton's staircase; I won't swear I said that but I did it—I cannot say whether Mrs. Seeley saw the palliasse in the back garden—she was not upstairs all the time—I said "Mrs. Seeley did not see the mattress go over the wall," that is true—Mrs. Seeley went to bed intoxicated that night, but she first went round the house to see if all was safe—I do not think she hardly knew what she was doing at the time of the removal—I do not think I have seen Mrs. Seeley go to Mrs. Charlton's; yes, she went that night, but she did not go usually at night—I did not say about the things being given Mrs. Charlton for moving before, because I forgot it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. W. SLEIGH</hi>. I said before the Magistrate, "When the goods were being removed from Hornsey Park Road, the defendants Charlton and Clayton were there—Mrs. Seeley told me she had given some goods to the Charltons—while we were in the front room in the Euston Road she said "I think it was very unkind of Mrs. Charlton not coming to help put the things straight, as I have given her a bedstead, a palliasse, a chest of drawers, and a washstand"—I helped Mrs. Charlton to move the palliasse downstairs in Mrs. Seeley's house, over the wall and up Mrs. Charlton's staircase—Mrs. Seeley was upstairs while the palliasse was being taken down—she was in the room while it was taken from it—she told me to help Mrs. Charlton to take it down—this was on the Wednesday afternoon.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-470" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-470" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-470" type="surname" value="WARD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-470" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES WARD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a carman, and work for Mr. Denman,. of Camden Town—I recollect moving some thing from Hornsey Park Road, and Mrs. Seeley, Mrs. Charlton, and the girl waiting for me—Mrs. Seeley said Clay<lb></lb>ton was her husband.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. MATHEWS</hi>. I have not been examined before to-day—I had a "speen" paper four weeks ago—I have never told anybody what I was coming to say.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I gave ray proof to the solicitors.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">By</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">THE COURT</hi>. I was going to take down the washstand, and Mrs. Seeley said "You cannot manage that yourself, my husband will help you"—Clayton was the only man there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">The prisoners received good characters.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">EMILY CHARLTON</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
